{"Q0":"Well, my hypothesis from the first experiment was confirmed: A and B are the same movement, but inverted. The processing variables involved mainly people/text vs. other objects or contextual elements, and foreground vs. background. The starting point has to be the person(s) in the picture, especially if in closeup, especially if they are looking at the camera/the viewer. Any text also calls attention first, and larger text is the priority. Humans vs. animals gave me less confidence (e.g. the picture involving the elephant and the rider), and pictures with no people or text in them were also harder to tell, but whichever trajectory that started at the center, or with the largest object, or with the one providing a clue to the scene as a whole, was usually the one I went with."}
